        <briefdescription>
<para>\par \b Module Contract\/ \:</para>
<para>\par \b Purpose\/ \:  To provide a composite converter that iterates through a configured chain of format-specific converters, using the first match to transform any document into a processable format. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>\par \b Scope\/ \:  Converter chain orchestration, MIME detection delegation, file permission hardening. \par \b Input\/ \:  converters: List[AbstractConverter] passed at construction. \par \b Output\/ \:  Converted file path (str). \par \b Links\/ \:  [USES_API(8): <ref refid="namespacededoc_1_1utils_1_1utils_1a0229d30283f3fe207a4d19bfb9667dfe" kindref="member">dedoc.utils.utils.get_mime_extension</ref>, dedoc.converters.AbstractConverter] \par \b Invariants\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>convert() always returns a valid file path (original or converted).</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Output file is always made world-readable via chmod. \par \b Rationale\/ \:</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para>Q: Why a chain pattern instead of a registry? A: Converter ordering matters (e.g., DOCX before generic binary). A list preserves user-specified priority. \par \b Changes\/ \:</para>
<para>LAST_CHANGE: [v1.0.0 — Added semantic markup and LDD logging] \par \b Module Map\/ \:</para>
<para>CLASS 9[Orchestrates ordered converter chain] =&gt; ConverterComposition \par \b Use Cases\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>[ConverterComposition.convert]: User (Upload) → FindSuitableConverter → ConvertedFileReturned </para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
